Part B
==============================================
Ethical issues and mitigations 
==============================================

a. Over reliance and loss of skill

What the risk is:
When developers use AI too much, they may start trusting its suggestions without thinking critically. 
This can weaken their own problem-solving skills over time — they might begin to depend on AI instead of learning core concepts deeply.

How I will personally mitigate it:
I will use AI as an assistant, not a replacement for my own thinking. I will try first to solve problems on my own,
and use AI as a guide or to check my logic or as an improvement suggestions. I don't ask it to write entire solutions for me without understanding them.

=======================================
b. Inaccurate or Misleading Suggestions

What the issue is:
AI doesn’t always produce correct answers. Sometimes it gives code that looks plausible but has bugs or doesn’t work in context. 
Because it can sound confident, developers might trust it without testing thoroughly.

How I will personally mitigate it:
I will always test AI-generated code thoroughly before using it in production. I will run tests, examine the logic, and make sure it fits the actual 
requirements instead of assuming it’s correct just because the AI suggested it.

=======================================
c. Data Exposure and Privacy Violations

What the issue is:
When developers paste real customer data, API keys, or proprietary information into an AI tool, that data can be processed and possibly stored outside the company. 
If that data is sensitive, this could violate privacy laws like GDPR or even expose secrets to others.

How I would personally mitigate it:
I would never input real production data or sensitive details into AI tools. 
Instead, I’d create anonymized or synthetic examples if I need help with debugging or writing SQL. I’d also avoid sharing credentials, schema details, or customer information with any third-party AI system.